# Update Related Comments After Changes

When you change code, update every comment that references the changed behavior, signature, names, values, or invariants — in the same edit. Stale comments are bugs.

## What counts as a "related comment"

- Inline comments next to the changed lines
- Block/JSDoc/docstring comments on the enclosing function, class, or module
- Comments referencing the symbol by name elsewhere in the file
- Comments in callers/callees that describe the changed contract (search the repo)
- Top-of-file headers, README snippets, and `AGENTS.md` notes that describe the changed area
- TODO/FIXME/NOTE/HACK markers that the change resolves or invalidates

## Required actions on every edit

1. After editing, scan the diff for any nearby comment that references the old behavior, name, type, parameter, return value, or constant.
2. Grep the repo for the renamed/removed symbol and update or delete any comment that references it.
3. If a comment becomes redundant or merely narrates the new code, delete it (per the project's no-narration comment guideline).
4. If a TODO/FIXME is resolved by the change, remove it.
5. Never leave a comment that contradicts the code. If unsure, delete the comment rather than leaving it stale.

## Examples

```js
// BAD: signature changed, comment still says "id"
// Looks up the user by id.
function getUser(email) { /* ... */ }

// GOOD
// Looks up the user by email.
function getUser(email) { /* ... */ }
```

```js
// BAD: behavior changed, TODO is now stale
// TODO: handle null case
function parse(input) {
  if (input == null) return null;
  return JSON.parse(input);
}

// GOOD: TODO removed because it's resolved
function parse(input) {
  if (input == null) return null;
  return JSON.parse(input);
}
```

```js
// BAD: renamed `loadMap` -> `loadLevel`, doc still references old name
// loadMap reads the map JSON and returns a Level.
export function loadLevel(name) { /* ... */ }

// GOOD
// loadLevel reads the map JSON and returns a Level.
export function loadLevel(name) { /* ... */ }
```

## Do not add narration

Updating comments does not mean adding new ones. Do not add comments that just restate what the code does. Only keep comments that explain non-obvious intent, trade-offs, or constraints.
